How appliance controllers should interpret caps

This server sends caps via OCPP SetChargingProfile:

chargingRateUnit = "W"

limit = <watts>

Appliance controller behavior should be appliance-specific:

EVSE: set max charging power/current

Water heater: throttle if possible; otherwise schedule/disable element with minimum cycle rules

Dryer: prefer delaying start; shed only when necessary

HVAC: avoid hard power cuts; enforce min off-time; adjust setpoints/duty cycles when possible

Range/oven: usually “non-flexible”; instead treat it as a trigger that forces other loads down

If you need richer semantics, this server supports custom controls via DataTransfer:

LoadLevelControl

ChargingRateUnitChange

What this server is trying to solve (summary)

Unified control plane for multiple high-power home loads

Single policy layer (caps + groups) instead of many vendor apps

Composable constraints using nested groups:

“Whole home” contains “HVAC” and “Laundry,” each with their own caps

Visibility into loading using OCPP metering:

per-load watts, per-group watts, and total watts

A practical stepping stone

Model B retrofit controllers today, Model A embedded OEM OCPP later

Next upgrades (optional)

Persistence (SQLite) for groups, limits, and history

TLS (WSS) termination via Caddy/Nginx (and optionally mTLS)

Auto-enforcement loop (apply caps periodically only when changed)

Integration with panel metering (treat as truth for total load)

Allocation solver (fair-share) instead of simple min() policy if desired
